dataIdInfo.idAbs:
For detailed information on how to query this data set and how layer file user views were derived go to Resource Details section in metadata for this file.

CoverType is a photo-interpreted delineation of the Tongass National Forest by land type and timber cover type. Classification of lands was done sequentially: 1) land and water identified; 2) forested and non-forested areas were identified; 3) forested areas were classified by forest type and forest productivity; and 4) productive forest lands were further characterized by volume class, tree size, species composition. The original classifications were based on photo-interpretation of 1:15840 aerial photographs in 1978. The minimum map unit size is approximately 10 acres, though the average area for forested polygons is 60 acres. Additionally, CoverType is updated for new stands created through natural events or management activity. The data has also been corrected for errors, as found, that occurred during the attributing and digitizing of the original classification data.

Data has been compiled for some lands in southeast Alaska outside National Forest System Ownership. Data collected outside NFS boundaries has been inconsistently collected and compiled and should not be used for data analysis..

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
Use of the CoverType layer to determine volume class has been controversial. Volume class (VOLC) in this dataset was determined by using aerial stand volume tables for Western hemlock and Sitka spruce based on stand height and crown closure information obtained from aerial photos. While volume class information is included in this layer, a direct correlation between forest structure (as exhibited by stand height and crown closure) and each volume class has not been established. For more information, see point_of_contact.
The dataset differentiates between 'forested' and 'non-forested' areas. 'Non-forested' land has either never supported forests, or are lands formerly forested where forest use is precluded by development for other uses. 'Forested' land is defined as land with at least 10 percent stocked by forest trees of any size or formerly having had such tree cover, and not currently developed for non-forest land. 'Forested' lands are further classified as either 'productive' or 'non-productive'. 'Productive' land is producing or capable of producing crops of industrial wood. This includes areas suitable for management to grow crops of industrial wood generally of a site quality capable of producing in excess of 20 cubic feet per acre of annual growth. This includes land capable of producing at least 8,000 board feet per acre. Permanently inoperable or non-stockable areas are excluded because they are not suitable for silviculture management. Conversely, non-stocked areas which are stockable and otherwise meet this definition are included. 'Unproductive' forest are all forested lands not included in the productive forest land classification. The productive forest areas are classified according to species (FTYPE), stand size class (SSIZEC), and volume class (VOLC). The FTYPE names are derived from the species or group of species with the plurality of basal area in sawtimber stands and number of stems in all other stands. In the field, forest stands are divided into size classes (SSIZEC) based on tree diameters and age. These broad classes can be fairly well recognized on aerial photos from the texture of the stand, height of the trees and diameter and shape of crowns. Stand size class is determined by the plurality of space occupied by all trees. Basal area is used as the basis for estimating plurality of space occupied by sawtimber trees and numbers of trees for poletimber and seedling-sapling tree sizes. Volume class (VOLC) was determined by using aerial stand volume tables for Western hemlock and Sitka spruce based on stand height and crown closure. While volume class information is included in the coverage, a direct correlation between forest structure (as exhibited by stand height and crown closure) and timber volume has not been established.
Dates of format YYYY/07/15 (July 15) show the approximate year of harvest based on photo interpretation where record of harvest was lost. These are estimates. +/- 10 years accuracy.
TEAMS updates for 2007-2011 and FY2012 are complete. Update applied on 11/30/2012. Update in Wrangell Island applied 01/08/2013. Saddle Lake updates was applied on 03/08/13.
The Past Harvest and Young Growth layer files set separate definition queries on the Cover Type feature class. In September 2015, GIS and Silviculture staff consulted and agreed that Cover Type is the most reliable layer from which to derive past harvest and young growth. Because the Vegetation and Activity layers were undergoing substantial revisions at this time, the specific queries were also assessed. It was agreed that the query to derive past harvest from Cover Type is STAND_ORIGIN = 'H' (in simple terms, Stand Origin is Harvest.) To derive young growth, the query is Stand_Origin = 'H' and Reserve_Amount < 50 and (Date_Origin is not NULL and Date_Origin > 0) Because all attributes have not been updated in Cover Type, the results of these queries include known errors and inconsistencies. Comparison of the layer files to aerial imagery, Activity Polygon, and FACTS data can be helpful in accuracy assessments. If the user is not familiar with the Cover Type attributes and their relationship to Activity Polygon and FACTS, he/she should consult with GIS and Silviculture staff to interpret the reliability of the output. Known issues with the past harvest layer file: -Past Harvests incorrectly diplaying in Misty Fiords National Monument. There are many stands in Misty Fiords NM and elsewhere on KMRD where the Stand_Origin field of Cover Type is incorrectly coded with H-Harvest. -Past Harvest On Private Lands. The date of origin for many past harvests on non-National Forest lands is not known. In these cases, the DATE_ORIGIN field is populated with "0". The DATE_ORIGIN field for many private harvests is populated with an estimated, and possibly inaccurate, date. Known issues with the young growth layer file: -Partial Harvests that are not Young Growth. Many older partial harvests (often in the beach fringe) do have the Date_Origin field populated in Cover Type, but do not have the Reserve_Amount field populated. This results in these stands being incorrectly included in the output of the layer file as Young Growth. NOTE: "Past Harvest" and "Young Growth" are not synonymous terms. The primary difference is that to derive 'Young Growth,' the Reserve_Amount field in Cover Type needs to be considered. Reserve_Amount refers to the percentage of the stand that was left on the landscape; in other words, the percentage that was not harvested. (You can look at the Reserve_UOM to see the Unit of Measure, either Trees per Acre or Percent Basal Area.) To count as 'Young Growth' the Reserve_Amount must be less than 50; that is, to be 'Young Growth' less than half of the original trees must remain. In contrast, a 'Past Harvest' could certainly have a Reserve_Amount greater than 50. A Helicopter harvest or high-grading harvest where something like 75% (or more) of the original trees are left would be considered "Past Harvest," but it would not be "Young Growth."

report.measDesc: TOPOLOGY: Dataset checked to confirm all polygons are closed. Polygon topology is present. Geometry errors have been checked for and corrected.

Portions of ice fields around Yakutat and north of Juneau were either never mapped or never brought into the GIS. Also, some state/private lands were mapped but never digitized. Certain information from the original mapping for condition, density class, and decadence rating were never brought into the GIS. Harvest data is included as needed. Units identified in the sale administrator's monthly report as having been yarded are updated on this layer. Only that portion of a unit that is harvested is modified. The remaining un-harvested portion of the unit will continue to be included in the original 'parent' polygon that it was part of prior to harvest activity. In other words, CoverType is an existing vegetation cover map, which displays the net area of the harvest, not the gross area. Harvest information for state/private lands is incomplete.

The three area coverages were joined into one coverage named Existing_veg. Slivers created where the coverages joined were corrected when appropriate.
Updated harvest stand information was added to the coverage by using IDENTITY with the MGDSTD coverage.
Converted existing_veg in coverage format to CoverType in ESRI's Arc Spatial Data Engine (SDE) corporate geodatabase format.
